New rules for the world economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Imagine that leading politicians from around the world would once again meet in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
Naturally, they would primarily address today's problems: the eurozone crisis, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. But dealing with these issues would force the assembled leaders to look beyond and reconsider the overall solidity of the world's economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles based on sound common sense for guiding the global economy that they might agree on.
(I discuss this more extensively in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. The markets must be deeply embedded in existing governance systems.
The idea that markets can regulate themselves suffered a fatal blow from the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other social institutions to support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They need the political acceptance that is brought about by a progressive taxation system, safety nets, and social security.
And all this applies equally to global markets.
#2 In the foreseeable future, democratic state governance should largely be organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may be somewhat weakened, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
That national governments will hand over significant control to transnational institutions is unlikely; moreover, harmonizing rules would not benefit societies with different needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the exception to this rule, although its current crisis seems to contradict it.
We often waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals, resulting in weak outcomes that represent the lowest common denominator between the major countries.
When international cooperation is considered "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the World Trade Organization's rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures exemplify this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic processes at home rather than undermining them.

#3 Pluralistic prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built on the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best meet their needs.
The US, Europe, and Japan have produced comparable levels of prosperity over the long term.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security systems, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these “models” – one per decade – will then be presented as the great success that everyone should emulate.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experimentation and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will promote such experimental spirit and evolutionary development rather than suppress it.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The preceding principles may appear harmless.
But they carry powerful implications that collide with the prevailing views of globalization advocates.
Such an implication is that individual countries have the right to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the tools to shape and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to “protect” them.
We should therefore accept that countries can retain national rules – such as tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect consumer health and safety – and that they may do so by erecting barriers at their borders when trade demonstrably threatens local practices that enjoy broad public support.
If proponents of globalization are right, calls for such protective measures will fail due to lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve so that conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of maintaining national regulations – can both be heard appropriately in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or finance to maintain values and rules within one's own country should not be confused with using such measures to impose those values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in ways that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
Similarly, they should not allow the US or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure tools to change labor market regulations, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.

6. International agreements for regulating interactions between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic steering functions of the world economy does not mean we should abandon international rules.
The Bretton Woods system ultimately also had clear rules, albeit ones that were limited in scope and depth.
A complete free-for-all would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds pass each other, rather than prescribing identical cars or uniform speed limits.
We should strive for a maximum level of globalization that is in line with maintaining space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot enjoy the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives these principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where such consultations actually take place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
For undemocratic states, therefore, less liberal rules must apply.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: globalization works best when you don't take it too far.
